h: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lyham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic Riad, Samir, Abir, Amin, Hala, Jamil, Nadim, Soad, Walid, Wedad.","Arabic (mainly from Lebanon and Syria): occupational name from <i>laḥḥām</i> ‘butcher’. This surname is found mostly among Christians."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William De Lyham was born about 1276, in Northumberland, England, United Kingdom, his father, Hugh De Lyham, was 27 and his mother, Lena, was 24. He married Mary about 1298. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died before 1348."},"et":{"Abt 1276–bef 1348":"umbes 1276–enne 1348","1276–1348":"1276–1348","1278–Male":"1278–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","1299–Female":"1299–Surnud","1302–Female":"1302–Surnud","1250–1328":"1250–1328","1254–Female":"1254–Surnud","ABT 1302":"umbes 1302","1250":"1250","Bef 1328":"enne 1328","1280":"1280","1348":"1348","bef 1348":"enn